repo.name: cython

body:
Part of supporting the 3.15 Stable ABI+freethreading.

I've picked these out of my larger cdef class changes because they're handled slightly differently to the others.  One thing that I've assumed is that we want to be able to access closure variables quickly (without going through the opaque lookup) so I've just created shadow `cur_scope` and `cur_scope_obj` variables where the `cur_scope` variable points directly to the useful data-structure.

commit.message:
Support opaque PyObject in cyfunction/fusedfunction

This is planning ahead a bit for when we want to support
Limited API + freethreading builds (which I'm strongly assuming
is coming in Python 3.15).  In this case PyObject will become
opaque because it's different between freethreaded and regular
builds and so Cython will need to handle most inheritance
without including PyObject into the type struct.

This PR only covers cyfunction/fusedfunction and not the rest
of the shared types, mostly as a proof of concept. I've also
not done it outside the Limited API, just because the regular
API does the weird "semi-inheritance from PyCFunction" trick.
For regular cdef classes there might be some value in giving
users individual control.
WIP of opaque objects on extension types

Move memoryview acquisition counting out of generic atomics code

It got moved when we moved the atomics code out of the memoryview
file (because it was being used more widely).  However it really
is specific to memoryviews so it makes most sense there.
Fix compilation with opaque types a bit

Clean up checks for tp_dictoffset

It is inherited which means that we don't need to redefine
it for classes that have dict via inheritance.

Instead we should allow "this class has a dictoffset" or
"one of its first bases has a dictoffset".

Factor out some common limited API/type slots code to
find the dictoffset of a type.

This change is part of the bigger changes to support
limited API in Python 3.15(t)+ - in this version the base
type won't be the first member of of the object struct,
therefore meaning that we can't easily get offsetof the
dictoffset. It's taken out because it's standalone so
it probably simplifies the review of that change in the future.

Fix size checks

They're a little limited in what we can do - we're not able
to determine if the C object is too small.

Lookup via offset instead

To avoid needing the GIL when doing attribute lookup
